    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-08-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-08-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="517"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d517">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/341</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Whitehouse</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-08-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 18, 1922</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received August 29.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2246</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s circular
                    telegram repeated to this Embassy through London on June 29th,<note n="77"
                        xml:id="d517fn77">See footnote 71, <ref target="#pg_734">p.
                        734</ref>.</note> regarding the shipment of arms and munitions of war to
                    China, I have the honor to enclose herewith copy and translation in triplicate
                    of the reply of the French Foreign Office.<note n="76" xml:id="d517fn76">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0860" n="740" xml:id="pg_740"/>
                <p>The French Government points out that an embargo already exists as to shipments
                    from French territory, but suggests that in view of the proposal of the British
                    Government that the Diplomatic Corps at Peking should deliberate again on the
                    definition and interpretation of arms and munitions, it might be advisable to
                    await the result of this new deliberation before formally confirming the
                    resolution contained in the Department’s telegram.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sheldon Whitehouse</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
